Basic Linear Model

Now we will run a mixed model. Here we will allow for random effects, which are specific effects for each individual.

mixed_model = lmer(Reaction ~ Days + (1 + Days|Subject), data = sleepstudy)

summary(mixed_model)
Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
Formula: Reaction ~ Days + (1 + Days | Subject)
   Data: sleepstudy

REML criterion at convergence: 1743.6

Scaled residuals: 
    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
-3.9536 -0.4634  0.0231  0.4634  5.1793 

Random effects:
 Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev. Corr
 Subject  (Intercept) 612.09   24.740       
          Days         35.07    5.922   0.07
 Residual             654.94   25.592       
Number of obs: 180, groups:  Subject, 18

Fixed effects:
            Estimate Std. Error t value
(Intercept)  251.405      6.825  36.838
Days          10.467      1.546   6.771

Correlation of Fixed Effects:
     (Intr)
Days -0.138

Three parts of the above output are the same as we would get using the lm function. The fixed effects coefficients are in fact identical, though we can see they have different standard errors. In addition, we have the residual variance and standard deviation. The latter is the same thing as the residual standard error from lm, but we can see its value is different. That unexplained variance has now been partitioned into different parts.

In this model we allow both intercepts and the coefficient for Days to vary by student. The estimated standard deviation tells what how much we would deviate from the normal effect (i.e.the fixed effects above) as we move from student to student, on average.

print(VarCorr(mixed_model), comp=c('Var', 'Std')) 
 Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev. Corr 
 Subject  (Intercept) 612.090  24.7404       
          Days         35.072   5.9221  0.066
 Residual             654.941  25.5918

We can get estimates of these individual specific deviations.

random_effects = ranef(mixed_model)$Subject
random_effects

Or we can add them to the fixed effects, allowing us to think in terms of random coefficients.

random_coefficients = coef(mixed_model)$Subject

As you can imagine, this would be notably better for prediction than assuming the same intercept and slope for everyone.

fixed_effects = fixef(mixed_model)
random_effects  = 
  random_coefficients %>% 
  mutate(Subject = factor(unique(sleepstudy$Subject)))

sleepstudy %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Days, Reaction)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Subject), alpha = .25) +
  geom_abline(
    aes(
      intercept = fixed_effects['(Intercept)'],
      slope = fixed_effects['Days']),
    color = 'darkred',
    size = 2) +
  geom_abline(
    aes(
      intercept = `(Intercept)`, 
      slope = Days,
      color = Subject),
    size = .5,
    alpha = .25,
    data = random_effects)

Each individual is allowed to have their own say, but we still refer to the general population effect.

library(gganimate)

# this may take up to a minute to produce, and will show in your viewer
sleepstudy %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Days, Reaction)) +
  geom_abline(
    aes(
      intercept = fixed_effects['(Intercept)'],
      slope = fixed_effects['Days']),
    color = 'darkred',
    size = 2,
    alpha = .01) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Subject), alpha = 1) +
  geom_abline(
    aes(
      intercept = `(Intercept)`, 
      slope = Days,
      group = Subject,
      color = Subject),
    size = .5,
    alpha = .25,
    data = random_effects) + 
  transition_states(Subject, 1, 1) +
  theme_minimal()
